# Component Structure

- Each React component should be in its own directory with PascalCase naming (e.g., Button, TextField)
- Every component directory must contain:
  - A main component file with the same name as the directory (e.g., Button.tsx)
  - An index.ts file that exports the component
- Component exports in index.ts files should use "export \* from" syntax
- For complex components requiring multiple subcomponents, use namespace pattern:
  - Create a Component.namespace.ts file to define the namespace exports
  - Export individual subcomponents from the main component file
  - Use the namespace export in the index.ts file
  - Example: Tabs component has Tabs.tsx (main component), Tabs.namespace.ts (namespace definitions), and index.ts exports `export * as Tabs from "./Tabs.namespace"`
- Maintain the established directory structure under apps/web/src/shared/ui/common

# Component Implementation

- Always import React at the top of component files
- Define proper TypeScript interfaces for component props
- Prefer arrow function syntax for component definitions
- Properly export all components for consumption
- Follow existing component patterns for consistency

# Utility Functions

- Utility functions should be properly exported
- Use TypeScript types and interfaces for all utility functions
- Place utility functions in the appropriate directory (apps/web/src/shared/lib/)
- Follow existing utility patterns for consistency

# Package Exports

- Ensure all components are properly exported from the main index.ts
- Main index should export all components from the components/index.ts file

# Code Style

- Never use the 'any' type in TypeScript - use proper typing
- Prefer arrow functions for component and function definitions
- Follow the project's code style and conventions
- Maintain consistent naming conventions across the codebase

# Build Configuration

- Ensure package.json has all necessary dependencies and build scripts
- Follow existing patterns for build and dependency management

Remember that this package is a part of the Seed Design system, which provides consistent UI components. When generating code, ensure it matches the existing structure and style of the package.
